literal "false"

\end_inset

, but who benefits and to what extent also depends on many factors including
 commodity, value chain structure, etc.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this paper, we look at inclusiveness of the maize value chain.
 Staple food supply chains have received much less attention in the literature.
 Most studies focus on complex high value and/or global commodity value
 chains, such as horticulture and dairy value chains.
 Exceptions include teff in Ethiopia.
 Often, these studies are specifically designed to study rural-urban linkages
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "VANDERCASTEELEN2018383"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
One novel feature of this study lies in a unique data set: a stack survey
 that preserves linkages between the different value chain actors.
 In particular, maize farmers were randomly sampled in selected maize growing
 areas.
 Farmers were then asked to indicate actors up- and down-stream the value
 chain.
 These links were preserved in the data, such that outcomes at one level
 of the value chain can be connected to outcomes at another level.
 This allows us to investigate how inequality at one level of the value
 chain is reproduced at other levels.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The article is organized as follows: The next section starts with the context.
 We then describe the structure of the maize value chain and provide some
 statistics to get a sense of the scale of the actors involved.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Context
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Maize is a strategically important crop for food security and economic growth
 in eastern Africa 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "doi:10.22434/IFAMR2016.0086"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
 In the case of Uganda, the maize industry has experienced significant increase
 in production and contributed to export growth despite dismal gains in
 productivity.
 Slow productivity growth is attributed to market and non-market factors.
 Firstly, market attributes have partly contributed to low productivity
 and market participation of upstream value chain actors due to poor price
 transmission and volatility with recurrent episodes of extremely low-price
 offers which tend to disincentivize several producers, yet it is not clear
 if episodes of high prices drive back more producers.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "daly2016maize"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 noted that at the downstream end, lack of communication of market signals
 and standards are an impediment to development of the maize value chain.
 Market organization and integration is also lacking yet it is critical
 to alleviating some market and non-market failures.
 Secondly, inter-temporal challenges such as limited commercial scale, low
 adoption of improved varieties, diseases, and poor postharvest handling
 have negatively impacted the maize sector.
 Consequently, poor postharvest handling has led to a growing concern on
 quality of maize delivered by producers/suppliers to buyers/processors.
 Maize quality is invariably affected at several nodes of the value chain
 right from the production to processor node depending on the practices
 adopted by the various actors.
 At production level, practices such as variety selection and drying of
 maize are key.
 At the processor level, limited capacity to invest in quality control systems
 undermines quality of maize processed and the products thereof.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Arguably, achieving symmetry in desired maize grain attributes for enhancement
 of quality would be hard for all actors due to misaligned primary motivation
 and understanding of quality differentiation.
 However, it can be hypothesized that under proper incentives, convergence
 in the need for maize quality would be tenable as a basis for both up-stream
 and down-stream value chain actors.
 To improve quality, traditional practices and institutional arrangements
 must change.
 In this sense, government and business actors need to drive voluntary and
 non-voluntary policing of adherence to quality.
 This calls for incentives since there are costs of quality associated with
 practices, search, selection, and bonding.
 The question then is who drives the need for quality in the value chain
 and do signals resonate along the entire value chain to cause change in
 practices? 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Aware of the need to improve quality of maize in Uganda, surprisingly, literatur
e is scarce on how various value chain actors consider and react to quality
 needs.
 Where coordination of interactions within the commodity value chain linkages
 is more buyer than producer driven, then, it can be said that the motivation
 and attention to quality is more imperative for the downstream than the
 upstream actors and thus, they bear greater part of risk and cost of quality.
 Premised on the mismatch in quality consideration, this study tries to
 assess the relationship between quality and the various practices by the
 various value chain actors.
 Such practices inter alia include: (1) at the input provider level, we
 have information on variety selection; (2) at production level we have
 farm management practices and technology adoption, and postharvest handling;
 (3) at the trader level we have information on grading and aggregation
 (3) at processor level we have information about processing.
 We assume that sensitivity to quality may explain some practices following
 the prevailing strengths and weaknesses in institutional conditions (as
 described below).
\end_layout

