\begin_layout Section
Hypothesis
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Outcomes related to quality at one particular point in the value chain are
 affected by quality considerations at other points in the value chain.
 For instance, value chains in which input providers supply low quality
 seed varieties lead to low quality maize meal at the level of the processor.
 Processors that predominantly produce lower quality meal (grade 1) result
 in farmers paying less attention to post harvest handling.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
One key part of the study will be to look at what is most important – the
 push of pull factor.
 Instrumental variables methodologies can be explored to investigate the
 direction of causality.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Conceptual framework 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Maize actors operate in an environment that has several institutional arrangemen
ts including policies, standards, and regulations that are meant for value
 chain actors to observe and achieve minimum maize quality and food safety
 standards.
 Six actors are profiled in the maize market space that is segmented into
 three categories of value chain actors namely upstream level which has
 input dealers and producers/farmers; midstream level which comprises of
 aggregators and buyers/traders; and the downstream level which has the
 processors, marketers, and distributors (to both in domestic and regional
 markets)
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
There are also the consumers, but as they do not add value to the product,
 we do not consider them part of the value chain in this study.
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 As we progress downstream, the linkage between the producers and buyers
 is thought to be loose to the extent that largely, random spot marketing
 is the common and dominant practice which may predicate a weak correlation
 between the upstream and downstream actors whose conduct generally affects
 the inter-relations and outcomes in terms of pricing and quality of the
 maize, and reputation value chain actors.
 The current situation seems that outcomes are not causing reforms, yet
 existing institutional arrangements appear ineffective to limit poor quality
 maize at levels not of economic importance to all value chain actors and
 the maize subsector.
\end_layout

